label.value: increased number of R-loops at tRNA genes

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA-DNA hybrid molecules is greater than normal at tRNA genes.

label.value: normal plasma membrane phosphatidylserine distribution

value.value: A localization phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the distribution of phosphatidylserine in the plasma membrane is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abnormal plasma membrane phosphatidylserine distribution

value.value: A localization phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the distribution of phosphatidylserine in the plasma membrane is abnormal.

label.value: increased protein phosphorylation during cellular response to UV

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a greater extent than normal during a cellular response to ultraviolet light.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal cell wall disassembly at cell fusion site

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which disassembly of the cell wall at the site of cell-cell fusion during mating is abnormal.

label.value: premature cell wall disassembly at cell fusion site

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which disassembly of the cell wall at the site of cell-cell fusion during mating begins earlier than normal, e.g. before pairing with a partner cell. Premature cell wall breakdown often results in cell lysis.

label.value: premature actin fusion focus assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which actin fusion focus assembly begins earlier than normal. An actin fusion focus normally forms during mating at the site where the two cells will fuse.

label.value: abolished protein localization to cell cortex of cell tip during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the cell cortex of one or both cell tips does not occur.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to actin fusion focus

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the actin fusion focus is abnormal.

definition.value: Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found associated with heterochromatin and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: multiple shmoo formation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which a cell forms two or more shmoos, usually in succession, without fusing with a partner cell. Cell fusion may or may not subsequently occur.

label.value: abolished protein localization to shmoo tip

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the tip of a shmoo, or mating projection, does not occur.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal RNA level during mitotic G1 phase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA measured in a cell during G1 phase of the mitotic cell cycle is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Total RNA or a specific RNA may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased subtelomeric DNA amplification during G0

value.value: A cell phenotype in which duplication of DNA sequences in the subtelomeric region occur more frequently than in wild type cells during G0 phase.

label.value: abnormal telomere morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the telomere is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal telomere organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal telomere morphology.

label.value: abnormal telomere length

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which telomere length is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal telomere organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal telomere morphology.

label.value: abnormal telomere structure

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which chromosome structure is abnormal at the telomeric regions. Telomere structure refers to the position, shape, arrangement and connectivity of DNA and associated proteins in the telomeric region.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal telomere organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal telomere morphology.

label.value: shortened telomeres during G0

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which cells form telomeres that are shorter than normal during G0 phase. Normally, telomere length is stable in G0, whereas telomere sequences can be lost in mutants.

label.value: normal telomere morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the telomere is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal telomere morphology during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the telomere is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.

label.value: normal telomere structure

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which chromosome structure is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) at the telomeric regions. Telomere structure refers to the position, shape, arrangement and connectivity of DNA and associated proteins in the telomeric region.

label.value: normal telomere length

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which telomere length is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal telomere length during G0

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which telomere length is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during G0 phase.

label.value: normal telomere structure during G0

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which chromosome structure is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) at the telomeric regions during G0 phase. Telomere structure refers to the position, shape, arrangement and connectivity of DNA and associated proteins in the telomeric region.

label.value: loss of viability in G0

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after entering G0 phase.

definition.value: Use this term to annotate experiments in which a culture is grown under nitrogen-depleted conditions until cells enter G0, and then the number of cells viable enough to form a colony upon return to conditions supporting vegetative growth is measured and compared to wild type.

label.value: decreased protein degradation during mitotic G1 phase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of protein degradation is decreased during G1 phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased cytoplasmic translation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of cytoplasmic translation is increased.

definition.value: Note that this term should be used only when an experiment measures the initiation of protein synthesis directly, e.g. by ribosome profiling. Consider annotating to 'decreased protein level' (FYPO:0000835) or one of its descendants.

label.value: abnormal mitotic sister chromatid cohesion

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitotic sister chromatid cohesion is abnormal. Mitotic sister chromatid cohesion is the process in which the sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome are joined along the entire length of the chromosome, from their formation in S phase through metaphase during a mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: loss of viability following cell cycle arrest at mitotic G2/M phase transition

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after arrest at the mitotic G2/M phase transition of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: Use this term to annotate experiments in which a culture is grown under conditions that arrest at the G2/M phase transition (e.g. restrictive temperature for a cdc mutant), and then the number of cells viable enough to form a colony upon return to conditions supporting vegetative growth is measured and compared to wild type.

label.value: loss of viability in stationary phase following entry from mitotic G2 phase

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after entering stationary phase following arrest at the mitotic G2/M phase transition of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: Use this term to annotate experiments in which a culture is grown under conditions that induce stationary phase entry from G2 phase (e.g. minimal medium lacking either glucose or sulfate), and then the number of cells viable enough to form a colony upon return to conditions supporting vegetative growth is measured and compared to wild type.

label.value: premature sister kinetochore separation during mitotic G2 phase

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which sister kinetochores separate during G2 phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: premature sister kinetochore separation during stationary phase

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which sister kinetochores of a replicated chromosome separate prematurely when the population in which the cell is found is in stationary phase.

label.value: abnormal meiosis II

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the second meiotic nuclear division is abnormal.

label.value: decreased proteolysis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of hydrolysis of peptide bonds within a protein is decreased. All proteolysis may be affected, or only cleavage of specific proteins, or even specific sites within specific proteins.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased proteolysis during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of hydrolysis of peptide bonds within a protein is decreased during the meiotic cell cycle. All proteolysis may be affected, or only cleavage of specific proteins, or even specific sites within specific proteins.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to centromere during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the centromere of a chromosome is abnormal during the meiotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to centromere during meiotic prophase II

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the centromere of a chromosome is abolished during prophase of the second meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: delayed onset of protein degradation during meiosis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype which protein degradation begins later than normal during one or both meiotic nuclear divisions.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to centromere during meiotic prophase II

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the centromere of a chromosome is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during prophase of the second meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to cell periphery

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the cell periphery is abnormal.

definition.value: Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found at the cell periphery and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to cell periphery during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the cell periphery does not occur when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to cell periphery during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the cell periphery is increased when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to cell periphery during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the cell periphery is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: loss of viability following cellular response to pheromone

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after exposure to a pheromone.

definition.value: Use this term to annotate experiments in which a culture is grown in the presence of hydroxyurea, and then the number of cells viable enough to form a colony upon hydroxyurea removal is measured and compared to wild type.

label.value: spheroid cell during cellular response to pheromone

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a cell is shaped in the form of a spheroid during a cellular response to a pheromone. In spheroid cells, there is much less difference between the long and short axes of the cell than in wild type. Spheroid cells may shorter than normal, with approximately the same diameter as normal, or they may be enlarged.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: multiseptate cell during cellular response to pheromone

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a cell contains more than one septum during a cellular response to a pheromone.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: abnormal actin cytoskeleton organization during cellular response to pheromone

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which actin cytoskeleton organization is abnormal during a cellular response to pheromone.

definition.value: Consider annotating to 'abnormal actin cytoskeleton' (FYPO:0002398), but note that an abnormal actin cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in a physically abnormal actin cytoskeleton.

label.value: decreased protein level during mating

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during mating is lower than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased RNA level during mitosis

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA measured in a cell during mitosis is higher than normal. Total RNA or a specific RNA may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein level during mitotic metaphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during metaphase of mitosis is higher than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased transcription during mitosis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which transcription occurs to a lower extent than normal during mitosis. All genes, or a specific subset of genes, may be affected.
